  <title class="- topic/title ">Tips for Targeting Groups</title>
  <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">The following tips will help you with
	 your targeting groups. 
  </shortdesc>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <othermeta name="solution" content="Target" />
      <othermeta name="topic" content="Advanced" />
    </metadata>
  </prolog>
  <refbody class="- topic/body        reference/refbody ">
    <refsyn id="refsyn_9A3F4E91FAF5451B93B60A2930BBBB4B" class="- topic/section     reference/refsyn ">
      <p class="- topic/p ">
        <ul id="ul_72FECD342F9D4147878E6C79FDA0A20E" class="- topic/ul ">
          <li id="li_BABD6B5C2E484DA98959127C268268FE" class="- topic/li "> All
			 standard JavaScript operators ( == != &lt; &gt; &amp;&amp; || etc.) can be
			 used, as well as accessible variables (for example,<codeph class="+ topic/ph pr-d/codeph "> landing.page.url</codeph>). 
		  </li>
          <li id="li_A22B3B0C75B54E07B33FF97633597536" class="- topic/li "> You
			 can reference both in-mbox and script 
			 <xref href="c_Profile_Parameters.xml#concept_01A30B4762D64CD5946B3AA38DC8A201" type="concept" format="dita" scope="local" class="- topic/xref ">profile
				parameters</xref>. By defining and collecting profile parameters including
			 time-on-site, lifetime monetary value and purchase frequency, you can use them
			 as building blocks in custom target group expressions. See the link below for a
			 full list of accessible variables and more examples. 
		  </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </refsyn>
